{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21b9f791-968a-485e-b22b-b70206ab72cc","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request boundary — the app has essentially one long-lived scope (the app lifetime). So `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext (and its change tracker) lives forever.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — a new instance per injection, closest to the \"fresh context per operation\" pattern.\n\n2. **Use `IDbContextFactory<T>`:**\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and create short-lived contexts:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = _factory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\n3. **Manually create scopes** with `IServiceScopeFactory` if you want scoped behavior tied to a page/viewmodel lifetime.\n\nOption 2 (`IDbContextFactory`) is the recommended pattern for MAUI/Blazor/desktop apps where there's no natural request scope.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c4199a25-6fbd-4000-8860-bf9a00dcd162","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request — the app has a single long-lived scope (essentially the app's lifetime), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. This means the DbContext is never disposed/recreated between page navigations, causing data to persist in the change tracker.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"A86D:29B0F9:6A43C9:7B7239:69FBE4CF"},"id":"c0fca183-2f6c-4f58-b547-11154c98d2b3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:03:22.804Z","parentId":"7afd256b-26a3-4972-b2d7-ef63b0412f38"}
